{"title_page": "Oyster pail", "text_new": "[[File:Oysterpail.jpg|thumb|alt=A plain oyster pail, lid opened, without a wire handle, containing plain [[white rice]] with a pair of [[chopsticks]] laid across the top|An opened, plain oyster pail of [[white rice]], with [[chopsticks]]]]\n\nAn '''oyster pail''' (also known as a '''Chinese food box''' or '''Chinese takeout container''') is a folded, [[wax]]ed or plastic coated, [[paperboard]] [[packaging|container]] originally designed to hold oysters.  It commonly comes with a handle made of [[Wire#Solid versus stranded|solid wire]].  Currently, it is often in use by [[American Chinese cuisine]] restaurants primarily throughout the United States, to package hot or cold [[take-out]] food. It can also sometimes be found in other Western countries, such as Australia, New Zealand, Germany, Poland and England, but is rarely seen in China and other Asian countries with high numbers of ethnic Chinese.\n\n== Uses ==\nThe container has the advantage of being inexpensive, durable and fairly leak-proof as long as it is kept upright. The top usually includes a locking paperboard tab so that it is self-closing. The simple [[origami]]-like folded construction also allows for some escape of [[steam]] from hot food. If care is used to remove the flaps, and the sides are unfolded, the container can also double as a one-time plate. It is more typica, however to eat directly out of the container, a feat that the long reach of [[chopsticks]] readily permits.The containers are primarily used with [[American Chinese cuisine]], though they have begun to spread in some European countries.\n\nOyster pails that can be used safely in [[microwave oven]]s (without the metal handle, which can cause [[electrical arcing|arcing]] in a microwave) are also available. Microwave-safe pails often come with no handle or a handle made of plastic.\n\nThe containers may also be used for storing or transporting non-food items, such as soap [[bath beads]] or small parts. Takeout containers have also been offered as novelty packaging for small gifts.<ref name=Hofmann>{{cite news|last=Hofmann|first=Deborah|title=New Gift Wraps: Gloss, Glitter and Ease|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/12/14/garden/new-gift-wraps-gloss-glitter-and-ease.html|accessdate=20 March 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=December 14, 1988}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nEarly patents date to 1890,<ref>{{cite patent\n | inventor-last =Wilcox\n | inventor-first =F W\n | inventor2-last =Moshier\n | inventor2-first =W D\n | publication-date =19 Apr 1890\n | title =Paper pail\n | country-code =US\n | description =\n | patent-number = 426698\n| url =http://www.google.com/patents/US426698\n| accessdate =28 Mar 2015}}</ref> 1894,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://patents.google.com/patent/US529053A/en|title=Paper pail|website=google.com}}</ref> and 1908.<ref>{{cite patent\n | inventor-last =Reber\n | inventor-first =J G\n | publication-date =28 April 1908\n | title =Oyster pail\n | country-code =US\n | description =\n| url =https://www.google.com/patents/US886074\n | patent-number = 886074}}</ref>  The paperboard oyster pail was invented at a time when fresh [[oyster]]s were more popular, more plentiful, and less expensive than they are at present. Since shucking oysters (removing the raw meat from the shell) takes some amount of skill and can be difficult and dangerous, it was common to have the oyster seller open the oysters so they could be taken home for use in cooked dishes. The oyster pail provided an inexpensive and sanitary way to accomplish this. In the early 20th century oyster pails were also used to hold [[honey]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=_p5lAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA75&dq=%22oyster+pail%22 |title=The ABC of bee culture: a cyclopaedia of every thing pertaining to the care ... - Amos Ives Root |publisher= Google Books |date= |accessdate=2012-12-12|year=1905 }}</ref> In the mid-20th century, [[overfishing]] (and the subsequent rise in price) of oysters left manufacturers with a significant number of unsold oyster pails.\n\n[[File:Oyster pail takeout box (2558467231).jpg|thumb|An oyster pail box from a Chinese restaurant]]\nHowever, in the US after [[World War II]], there was a huge increase in sales of prepared foods that could be purchased from restaurants, and heated or finished at home. [[Chinese food]] proved to be a popular choice, since it was tasty, unusual, fairly inexpensive and traveled well. The oyster pail was quickly adopted for \"Chinese [[takeout]]\". The paperboard pails were to some extent self-[[Thermal insulation|insulating]], and could be used for a wide variety of foods including cooked [[rice]], moist dishes such as [[egg foo young]] and [[sauce]]d dishes, though they were generally unsuitable for hot highly liquid dishes such as [[soup]]s.\n\nThe containers are also used by restaurants offering classic American takeout food, such as [[French fries]] or [[fried clams]], but the paperboard containers have become strongly associated with Chinese takeout in popular culture.  In 2011, the [[Smithsonian National Museum of American History]]<nowiki/> displayed iconic Chinese takeout containers in its exhibit ''Sweet & Sour: A Look at the History of Chinese Food in the United States''.<ref name=SNMAH>{{cite web|title=Sweet & Sour: A Look at the History of Chinese Food in the United States|url=http://apanews.si.edu/2011/03/04/sweet-and-sour-showcase/|work=Smithsonian Asian Pacific American Center|publisher=Smithsonian National Museum of American History|accessdate=20 March 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130414162829/http://apanews.si.edu/2011/03/04/sweet-and-sour-showcase/|archivedate=14 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Food}}\n* [[Foam food container]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Paper products}}\n{{packaging}}\n\n[[Category:Food packaging]]\n[[Category:American Chinese cuisine]]\n[[Category:Food storage containers]]\n[[Category:Oysters]]\n[[Category:Paper products]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Oysterpail.jpg|thumb|alt=A plain oyster pail, lid opened, without a wire handle, containing plain [[white rice]] with a pair of [[chopsticks]] laid across the top|An opened, plain oyster pail of [[white rice]], with [[chopsticks]]]]\n\nAn '''oyster pail''' (also known as a '''Chinese food box''' or '''Chinese takeout container''') is a folded, [[wax]]ed or plastic coated, [[paperboard]] [[packaging|container]] originally designed to hold oysters.  It commonly comes with a handle made of [[Wire#Solid versus stranded|solid wire]].  Currently, it is often in use by [[American Chinese cuisine]] restaurants primarily throughout the United States, to package hot or cold [[take-out]] food. It can also sometimes be found in other Western countries, such as Australia, New Zealand, Germany, Poland and England, but is rarely seen in China and other Asian countries with high numbers of ethnic Chinese.\n\n== Uses ==\nThe container has the advantage of being inexpensive, durable and fairly leak-proof as long as it is kept upright. The top usually includes a locking paperboard tab so that it is self-closing. The simple [[origami]]-like folded construction also allows for some escape of [[steam]] from hot food. If care is used to remove the flaps, and the sides are unfolded, the container can also double as a somewhat flimsy plate. However it is also typical to eat directly out of the container, a feat that the long reach of [[chopsticks]] makes easier. The containers are primarily used with [[American Chinese cuisine]], though they have started to spread in some European countries.\n\nOyster pails that can be used safely in [[microwave oven]]s (without the metal handle, which can cause [[electrical arcing|arcing]] in a microwave) are also available. Microwave-safe pails often come with no handle or a handle made of plastic.\n\nThe containers may also be used for storing or transporting non-food items, such as soap [[bath beads]] or small parts. Takeout containers have also been offered as novelty packaging for small gifts.<ref name=Hofmann>{{cite news|last=Hofmann|first=Deborah|title=New Gift Wraps: Gloss, Glitter and Ease|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/12/14/garden/new-gift-wraps-gloss-glitter-and-ease.html|accessdate=20 March 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=December 14, 1988}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nEarly patents date to 1890,<ref>{{cite patent\n | inventor-last =Wilcox\n | inventor-first =F W\n | inventor2-last =Moshier\n | inventor2-first =W D\n | publication-date =19 Apr 1890\n | title =Paper pail\n | country-code =US\n | description =\n | patent-number = 426698\n| url =http://www.google.com/patents/US426698\n| accessdate =28 Mar 2015}}</ref> 1894,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://patents.google.com/patent/US529053A/en|title=Paper pail|website=google.com}}</ref> and 1908.<ref>{{cite patent\n | inventor-last =Reber\n | inventor-first =J G\n | publication-date =28 April 1908\n | title =Oyster pail\n | country-code =US\n | description =\n| url =https://www.google.com/patents/US886074\n | patent-number = 886074}}</ref>  The paperboard oyster pail was invented at a time when fresh [[oyster]]s were more popular, more plentiful, and less expensive than they are at present. Since shucking oysters (removing the raw meat from the shell) takes some amount of skill and can be difficult and dangerous, it was common to have the oyster seller open the oysters so they could be taken home for use in cooked dishes. The oyster pail provided an inexpensive and sanitary way to accomplish this. In the early 20th century oyster pails were also used to hold [[honey]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=_p5lAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA75&dq=%22oyster+pail%22 |title=The ABC of bee culture: a cyclopaedia of every thing pertaining to the care ... - Amos Ives Root |publisher= Google Books |date= |accessdate=2012-12-12|year=1905 }}</ref> In the mid-20th century, [[overfishing]] (and the subsequent rise in price) of oysters left manufacturers with a significant number of unsold oyster pails.\n\n[[File:Oyster pail takeout box (2558467231).jpg|thumb|An oyster pail box from a Chinese restaurant]]\nHowever, in the US after [[World War II]], there was a huge increase in sales of prepared foods that could be purchased from restaurants, and heated or finished at home. [[Chinese food]] proved to be a popular choice, since it was tasty, unusual, fairly inexpensive and traveled well. The oyster pail was quickly adopted for \"Chinese [[takeout]]\". The paperboard pails were to some extent self-[[Thermal insulation|insulating]], and could be used for a wide variety of foods including cooked [[rice]], moist dishes such as [[egg foo young]] and [[sauce]]d dishes, though they were generally unsuitable for hot highly liquid dishes such as [[soup]]s.\n\nThe containers are also used by restaurants offering classic American takeout food, such as [[French fries]] or [[fried clams]], but the paperboard containers have become strongly associated with Chinese takeout in popular culture.  In 2011, the [[Smithsonian National Museum of American History]]<nowiki/> displayed iconic Chinese takeout containers in its exhibit ''Sweet & Sour: A Look at the History of Chinese Food in the United States''.<ref name=SNMAH>{{cite web|title=Sweet & Sour: A Look at the History of Chinese Food in the United States|url=http://apanews.si.edu/2011/03/04/sweet-and-sour-showcase/|work=Smithsonian Asian Pacific American Center|publisher=Smithsonian National Museum of American History|accessdate=20 March 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130414162829/http://apanews.si.edu/2011/03/04/sweet-and-sour-showcase/|archivedate=14 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Food}}\n* [[Foam food container]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Paper products}}\n{{packaging}}\n\n[[Category:Food packaging]]\n[[Category:American Chinese cuisine]]\n[[Category:Food storage containers]]\n[[Category:Oysters]]\n[[Category:Paper products]]\n", "name_user": "Kencf0618", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eUses", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oyster_pail"}
{"title_page": "Marcus Scribner", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Marcus Scribner\n| image              = Marcus Scribner by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Scribner at the 2019 [[WonderCon]] for ''[[She-Ra and the Princesses of Power]]''\n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|2000|1|7|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|2020|1|7|2000|1|7}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date)  -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = American\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Actor, voice actor\n| years_active       = 2010\u2013present\n| notable_works      = ''[[Black-ish]]''\n}}\n\n'''Marcus Scribner''' (born January 7, 2000)<ref>{{cite tweet |last= Scribner |first= Marcus |author-link= Marcus Scribner |user= MarcusScribner |number=949853560077828101 |date= January 6, 2018 |title= As you guys may or may not know tomorrow is ya boy's birthday!!!|language= English |link= https://twitter.com/MarcusScribner/status/949853560077828101 |access-date= January 13, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.upi.com/Top_News/2019/01/07/UPI-Almanac-for-Monday-Jan-7-2019/6991546835238/?ur3=1|title= UPI Almanac for Monday, Jan, 7, 2019 |agency=[[United Press International]]|date= January 7, 2019|accessdate=September 21, 2019|archivedate= September 21, 2019|archiveurl= http://archive.is/vtUh2/| url-status=live|quote= actor Marcus Scribner in 2000 (age 19)}}</ref> is an American actor. He is best known for starring as Andre Johnson Jr. on the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] [[sitcom]] ''[[Black-ish]]'' and voicing the character [[Bow (Masters of the Universe)|Bow]] in the critically acclaimed [[Netflix]] animated series ''[[She-Ra and the Princesses of Power]]''.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nScribner was born and raised in Los Angeles. His [[Marcus (name)|name]] is derived from Roman and Greek mythology, like that of his father Troy and sister Athena. Scribner also has a dog named Zeus whom he adopted as a puppy to commemorate his first professional acting job.<ref name=ABCBio>{{cite web|url=https://abc.go.com/shows/blackish/cast/marcus-scribner|title=Marcus Scribner as Andre Johnson, Jr. |work=[[Black-ish]]|publisher=[[American Broadcasting Company]]|accessdate=January 13, 2018}}</ref> Similar to his character on ''Black-ish'', his father is black while his mother is mixed (black and white).<ref name=TeenVogue111417>{{cite web|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/blackish-star-marcus-scribner-multiracial-environmentalism|title=\"Black-ish\" Star Marcus Scribner on Being Multiracial, His Environmentalism, and How the Show Is Just Like His Real Life|date=November 14, 2017|first=Gabe|last=Bergado|work=[[Teen Vogue]]|publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]]|accessdate=January 13, 2018}}</ref> His father's family is from Los Angeles while his maternal grandmother is from [[England]].<ref name=LADN112315>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailynews.com/2015/11/23/black-ishs-marcus-scribner-in-the-good-dinosaur/|title=Black-ish's Marcus Scribner in The Good Dinosaur|date=November 23, 2015|first=Bob|last=Strauss|work=[[Los Angeles Daily News]]|publisher=[[Digital First Media]]|accessdate=January 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blackamericaweb.com/2015/11/18/marcus-scribner-of-black-ish-talks-fun-on-and-off-set-and-how-education-is-as-important-as-acting/|title=Marcus Scribner Of 'black-ish' Talks Fun On And Off Set And How Education Is As Important As Acting|date=November 18, 2015|first=Tonya|last=Pendleton|website=BlackAmericaWeb.com|publisher=BlackAmericaWeb.com, Inc.|accessdate=January 13, 2018}}</ref> Scribner attended an Elementary School where most of the kids were Jewish.<ref name=TeenVogue111417/> He began studying acting at age seven.<ref name=iaam121214>{{cite web|url=http://www.iaam.com/magazine/magazine/Hollywoods-Hottest-New-Star--Marcus-Scribner#.WlpSkbynHcc|title=Hollywood's Hottest New Star - Marcus Scribner|date=December 12, 2014|work=iaam.com|first=Joshua|last=Chenault|accessdate=January 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180114184105/http://www.iaam.com/magazine/magazine/Hollywoods-Hottest-New-Star--Marcus-Scribner#.WlpSkbynHcc|archive-date=January 14, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> At the time he was very shy and didn't have any hobbies. In addition to sports, Scribner took an acting class and immediately fell in love with it. From that point, Scribner took acting classes on the weekends.<ref name=Wonderland>{{cite web|url=https://www.wonderlandmagazine.com/2017/10/03/marcus-scribner/|title=Marcus Scribner|first=Clarice|last=Metzger|work=Wonderland|date=October 3, 2017}}</ref> Scribner later admitted that at the time, he was afraid of getting injured.<ref name=LADN112315/> Despite that, he enjoys sports such as basketball and lacrosse and also loves video games.<ref name=BCK030615>{{cite web|url=https://bckonline.com/2015/03/06/exclusive-black-ish-star-marcus-scribner-has-a-candid-conversation-about-life-as-a-teen-star-and-future-plans/|title=EXCLUSIVE: 'BLACK-ISH' STAR MARCUS SCRIBNER HAS A CANDID CONVERSATION ABOUT LIFE AS A TEEN STAR AND FUTURE PLANS|author=Sarie|date=March 6, 2015|work=BCK Online|accessdate=January 13, 2018}}</ref>  When he was in kindergarten, Scribner hit his head on concrete while playing basketball and had to get five staples.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://screenertv.com/television/black-ish-marcus-scribner-destiny-ones-to-watch/|title=Meet 'Black-ish' star Marcus Scribner, a gamer, bacon-lover and 23 more facts|date=September 23, 2014|first=Terri|last=Schwartz|work=|accessdate=January 13, 2018}}</ref> Scribner started playing the [[clarinet]] in fifth grade.<ref name=EW121814>{{cite web|url=http://community.ew.com/2014/12/18/marcus-scribner-black-ish-naacp/|title='black-ish' star Marcus Scribner talks NAACP Image Award nomination|first=Monique|last=Jones|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|date=December 18, 2014|accessdate=January 13, 2018}}</ref> Though Scribner started at public high school in 2014, by early 2015, he was enrolled in home school to accommodate his work schedule.<ref name=BCK030615/>\n\n== Career ==\nWhen he was 10 years old, Scribner booked his first guest-star role on the ABC crime [[Comedy-drama|dramedy]] ''[[Castle (TV series)|Castle]]''.<ref name=Wonderland/> Scribner would go on to appear in an episodes of [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]'s ''[[New Girl]]'', [[TBS (U.S. TV channel)|TBS]]' ''[[Wedding Band]]'' and [[Nickelodeon]]'s ''[[Wendell & Vinnie]]''.<ref name=iaam121214/> At the age of 14, Scribner booked his first major role when he was cast in the role Andre Johnson Jr. in the ABC sitcom ''[[Black-ish]]'' opposite [[Anthony Anderson]], [[Tracee Ellis Ross]], [[Laurence Fishburne]] and [[Jenifer Lewis]].<ref name=Nylon100317>{{cite web|url=https://nylon.com/articles/marcus-scribner-blackish-interview|title=Marcus Scribner Of 'Black-Ish' Is Making Nerds Cool Again|date=October 3, 2017|first=Taylor|last=Bryant|work=[[Nylon (magazine)|Nylon]]|publisher=Diversis Capital|accessdate=January 13, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Wonderland/> Scribner actually beat out Anderson's own son Nathan for the role.<ref name=Nylon100317/> In an interview with ''[[Teen Vogue]]'', the actor explained that he heavily identified with the show.<ref name=TeenVogue111417/> Scribner was 13 when he first auditioned for the series and 14 years old when the pilot was filmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvinsider.com/647628/marcus-scribner-blackish-abc/|title='black-ish' Star Marcus Scribner Is All Grown up|date=October 31, 2017|first=Damian|last=Holbrook|work=[[TV Guide#TV Insider|TV Insider]]|publisher=TVGM Holdings, LLC|accessdate=January 13, 2018}}</ref> Scribner received an [[NAACP Image Award]] nomination for [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Comedy]] for his portrayal of Junior in the [[Black-ish (season 1)|first season]].<ref name=EW121814/> In 2015, Scribner voiced Buck in [[Pixar]]'s animated film ''[[The Good Dinosaur]]''.<ref name=\"TGD-Recast\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.disney.com/insider/2015/06/12/meet-the-new-cast-of-disneypixars-the-good-dinosaur/|title=Meet the New Cast of Disney\u2022Pixar's The Good Dinosaur |publisher=The Walt Disney Company|date= June 12, 2015|accessdate=June 12, 2015}}</ref> In 2016, Scribner began voicing the recurring role of Smudge as a guest star on the [[Netflix]] animated series ''[[Home: Adventures with Tip & Oh]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lamanagement.co/marcus-scribner-guest-stars-on-netflix-spinoff-of-dreamworks-home/|title=MARCUS SCRIBNER GUEST STARS ON NETFLIX SPINOFF OF DREAMWORK'S HOME|date=September 20, 2016|publisher=LA Management|accessdate=January 13, 2018}}</ref> Later that summer Scribner started production on the Independent comedy ''Alexander IRL'' opposite [[Nathan Kress]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/brent-rivera-nathan-kress-alexander-irl-1201817936/|title=Brent Rivera, Nathan Kress to Star in 'Alexander IRL' (EXCLUSIVE)|date=July 20, 2016|first=Dave|last=McNary|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|accessdate=January 13, 2018}}</ref> With the launch of the [[Freeform (TV channel)|Freeform]] spin-off ''[[Grown-ish]]'', Scribner takes on a more prominent role during the [[Black-ish (season 4)|fourth season]] of ''Black-ish''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2017/10/marcus-scribner-black-ish-season-4-interview|title=Marcus Scribner Is Stepping Into A Senior Position on This Season of 'black-ish'|date=October 3, 2017|author=Khal|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|publisher=Complex Media, Inc.|accessdate=January 13, 2018}}</ref> In 2018, it was announced that Scribner would star in thriller \"Confessional.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/marcus-scribner-paris-berelc-thriller-confessional-1202731241/|title=Marcus Scribner, Paris Berelc Starring in Thriller 'Confessional'|date=March 20, 2018|first=Dave|last=McNary|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|accessdate=March 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\nScribner voiced [[Bow (Masters of the Universe)|Bow]] in the animated [[Netflix]] series, ''[[She-Ra and the Princesses of Power]]''. As his name suggests, Bow is a skilled archer. Bow is also the best friend of [[Glimmer (She-Ra)|Glimmer]] and [[She-Ra]].\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 2015 || ''[[The Good Dinosaur]]'' || Buck {{small|(voice)}} || Animated film\n|-\n| 2017 || ''[[Alexander IRL]]'' || Darius || [[YouTube Red]] original film\n|-\n| TBA || ''Confessional'' || TBA || Lead role \n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[Castle (TV series)|Castle]]'' || Tim Thornton || Episode: \"[[Castle (season 2)#Episodes|Den of Thieves]]\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2012 || ''[[New Girl]]'' || Toby || Episode: \"[[New Girl (season 1)#Episodes|Control]]\" \n|-\n| ''[[Wedding Band]]'' || Ben || Episode: \"[[Wedding Band#Episodes|Get Down on It]]\"\n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[Wendell & Vinnie]]'' || Graham || Episode: \"[[Wendell & Vinnie#Episodes|Valentines & the Cultural Experience]]\"\n|-\n| 2014 || ''[[Black-ish]]'' || Andre Johnson Jr. || Main role\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2016 || ''[[American Dad!]]'' || Movie Goer {{small|(voice)}} || Episode: \"[[American Dad! (season 13)#Episodes|Garfield and Friends]]\"\n|-\n| ''[[Home: Adventures with Tip & Oh]]'' || Smudge {{small|(voice)}} || {{show\n|1= 6 episodes and film\n|2 = Episode: \"[[List of Home: Adventures with Tip & Oh episodes#season 1 (2016)|Kung Boov]]\" {{small|(2016)}} <br> Episode: \"[[List of Home: Adventures with Tip & Oh episodes#seas