nstruction]].\n\nIn its first century Texas was a Democratic bastion, only voting for another party once \u2013 in 1928 when anti-Catholic sentiment against Al Smith drove voters to Republican Herbert Hoover. A gradual trend towards increasing social liberalism in the Democratic Party, however, has turned the state (apart from Hispanic [[South Texas]], the [[Trans-Pecos]] and several large cities) into a Republican stronghold. Since 1980 Texas has voted [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] in every election.\n\nWinners of the state are in '''bold'''.\n\n==Elections from 1864 to present==\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Winner (nationally)\n! Votes\n! Percent\n! Loser (nationally)\n! Votes\n! Percent\n! Other national<br>candidates{{efn|name=\"national\"|For purposes of these lists, other national candidates are defined as those who won at least one electoral vote, or won at least ten percent of the vote in multiple states.}}\n! Votes\n! Percent\n! Electoral<br>Votes\n! Notes\n|-\n| [[2016 United States presidential election in Texas|2016]] || '''[[Donald Trump]]'''<ref name=\"PV\">[[United States presidential elections in which the winner lost the popular vote|Won the electoral college while losing the popular vote]].</ref> || 4,685,047 || 52.10 || [[Hillary Clinton]] || 3,877,868 || 43.12 ||\u2014\n|  || || 38 || Two faithless electors, one voting for [[John Kasich]], another for [[Ron Paul]].\n|-\n| [[2012 United States presidential election in Texas|2012]] || [[Barack Obama]] || 3,308,124 || 41.38 || '''[[Mitt Romney]]''' || 4,569,843 || 57.17 ||\u2014\n|  || || 38 || \n|-\n| [[2008 United States presidential election in Texas|2008]] || [[Barack Obama]] || 3,528,633 || 43.68 || '''[[John McCain]]''' || 4,479,328 || 55.45 ||\u2014\n|  || || 34 || \n|-\n| [[2004 United States presidential election in Texas|2004]] || '''[[George W. Bush]]''' || 4,526,917 || 61.09 || [[John Kerry]] || 2,832,704 || 38.22 ||\u2014\n|  || || 34 || \n|-\n| [[